olice about 13 months to track down the owner of the single latent fingerprint left on the windows of Dr. Wineinger's car. Jake was arrested by Detective Paul Quyle after Quyle found a cache of weapons in a house he had rented to Fleagle in [[Stockton, California]] in March 1929. His fingerprints were sent to the Bureau of Investigation (later known as the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]) in [[Washington DC]], where they were identified as Jake Fleagle and connected to the Lamar bank robbery. The Stockton Police had released Jake after fingerprinting. Ralph was arrested first in [[Kankakee, Illinois]] and after flying back to Kansas and being booked in Lamar he was taken to Colorado Springs where he eventually confessed. Ralph agreed to provide authorities with information about the rest of the gang in exchange for the release of his two brothers Fred and Walt Fleagle. A nationwide manhunt for Jake resulted in his death in a [[shootout]] on a train in [[Branson, Missouri]], in October 1930 after his brother had been [[hanged]] in Colorado. Royston was captured at his home in San Andreas, California, and Abshier was arrested in [[Grand Junction, Colorado]].\n\n==Legal process==\nThe three were tried first in Lamar, Colorado, and in a sensational series of trials in October and November 1929, and they were all sentenced to hang.\n\nTheir appeals to the Colorado Supreme Court did not succeed, and the men were executed over a two-week period in mid-July 1930. This was the very first time the FBI used a single fingerprint to convict someone of a crime, and was a major success for the [[FBI]].\n\n==Treasure==\nEven today treasure hunters scour the west looking for the caches of loot supposedly buried by skinflint Ralph Fleagle. Credible rumors, but little proof, abound about unrecovered loot buried in California, Kansas and possibly Missouri. There is evidence that Ralph invested much of his money, and possibly owned an apartment building in San Francisco, where he had been living before being arrested in [[Kankakee, Illinois]]. Ralph's wife Margaret was sent away by the Fleagle family shortly after Ralph was hanged in Colorado, but there is no evidence of where she went.\n\n==Sources==\n*''Abshier v. People'', No. 12,558., Supreme Court of Colorado, 87 Colo. 507; 289 P. 1081; 1930 Colo. [[LEXIS]] 258, June 9, 1930\n*''Royston v. People'', No. 12,559., Supreme Court of Colorado, 87 Colo. 529; 289 P. 1077; 1930 Colo. LEXIS 259, June 9, 1930\n*''Fleagle v. People'', No. 12,580., Supreme Court of Colorado, 87 Colo. 532; 289 P. 1078; 1930 Colo. LEXIS 260, June 9, 1930\n*The Fleagle Gang, by N.T. Betz {{ISBN|978-1-4208-1761-4}} (2005 Authorhouse)\n\n[[Category:American bank robbers]]\n[[Category:1928 in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Hydrargyrum", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eManhunt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fleagle_Gang"}
{"title_page": "Grant's bushbaby", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Grant's bushbaby<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Primates | heading= ''Galago granti''| id= 12100138 |pages= 125}}</ref>\n| image = Galago granti.jpg\n| image_caption = Juvenile (approx. 4 months)\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn | author= de Jong, Y.A | author2= Butynski, T.M. | author3= Perkin, A. | title= ''Paragalago granti'' | year= 2019 | page= e.T91970347A17962454 | access-date= 16 March 2020}}</ref>\n| genus = Paragalago\n| species = granti\n| authority = ([[Oldfield Thomas|Thomas]] & [[Robert Charles Wroughton|Wroughton]], 1907)\n| synonyms = \n| range_map = Grant's Bushbaby area.png\n| range_map_caption = Grant's bushbaby range\n}}\n\n'''Grant's bushbaby''' (''Paragalago granti''<ref name=\"Masters2017\">{{cite journal|last1= Masters|first1= J.C.|last2= G\u00e9nin|first2= F.|last3= Couette|first3= S.|last4= Groves|first4= C.P.|last5= Nash|first5= S.D.|last6= Delpero|first6= M.|last7= Pozzi|first7= L.|title=A new genus for the eastern dwarf galagos (Primates: Galagidae) |journal= Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society |volume= 181|issue= 1|year= 2017|pages= 229\u2013241|doi= 10.1093/zoolinnean/zlw028}}</ref>), also known as '''Grant's lesser bushbaby''' or the '''Mozambique lesser bushbaby''', is a species of [[primate]] in the family [[Galagidae]]. It is found in [[Malawi]], [[Mozambique]], [[Tanzania]], and [[Zimbabwe]]. Its natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical dry [[forest]]s. It is a common species and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] has assessed its conservation status as being of \"[[Least-concern species|least concern]]\".<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==Description==\nGrant's bushbaby is a small galago with a long, slender, well-furred tail. The sexes are similar. The forehead is pale grey and the crown darker grey, the eyes are surrounded by blackish eye-rings, and this black colour continues along the snout. There is a pale band running down the snout from forehead to nostrils. The ears are long and broad, with rounded tips, and are black on the outside. The general colour of the pelage is drab brown, the tip of each hair being buffy-brown. The outside of each limb is drab brown, gradually fading to whitish at the feet. The cheeks, throat and underparts are creamy-buff, the basal part of each hair being grey. The tail is elongated and bushy, drab brown with a blackened tip.<ref name=Kingdon>{{cite book|author1=Jonathan Kingdon|author2=David Happold|author3=Thomas Butynski|author4=Michael Hoffmann|author5=Meredith Happold|author6=Jan Kalina|title=Mammals of Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B_07noCPc4kC&pg=PA454 |year=2013 |publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-1-4081-8996-2 |pages=454\u2013455}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nGrant's bushbaby is native to Tanzania, Malawi, Mozambique and Zimbabwe. It occurs near the East African coast in the area between the [[Rufiji River]] in Tanzania, southwards to the [[Limpopo River]] in southern Mozambique. There are also inland populations, separate from the coastal ones. It occurs at least as high as {{convert|1800|m|ft|-2|abbr=on}} in the [[Thyolo Mountains]] in Malawi and in the [[Chimanimani District|Chimanimani]] region of Zimbabwe. It inhabits coastal and montane mixed forest, gallery forests and [[miombo]] woodland.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Galagidae nav}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q28156643}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:bushbaby, Grant's}}\n[[Category:Galagos|Grant's bushbaby]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Malawi]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Fauna of East Africa]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1907|Grant's bushbaby]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Grant's bushbaby<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Primates | heading= ''Galago granti''| id= 12100138 |pages= 125}}</ref>\n| image = Galago granti.jpg\n| image_caption = Juvenile (approx. 4 months)\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn | author= de Jong, Y.A | author2= Butynski, T.M. | author3= Perkin, A. | title= ''Paragalago granti'' | year= 2019 | page= e.T91970347A17962454 | access-date= 16 March 2020}}</ref>\n| genus = Paragalago\n| species = granti\n| authority = ([[Oldfield Thomas|Thomas]] & [[Robert Charles Wroughton|Wroughton]], 1907)\n| synonyms = \n| range_map = Grant's Bushbaby area.png\n| range_map_caption = Grant's bushbaby range\n}}\n\n'''Grant's bushbaby''' (''Paragalago granti''<ref name=\"Masters2017\">{{cite journal|last1= Masters|first1= J.C.|last2= G\u00e9nin|first2= F.|last3= Couette|first3= S.|last4= Groves|first4= C.P.|last5= Nash|first5= S.D.|last6= Delpero|first6= M.|last7= Pozzi|first7= L.|title=A new genus for the eastern dwarf galagos (Primates: Galagidae) |journal= Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society |volume= 181|issue= 1|year= 2017|pages= 229\u2013241|doi= 10.1093/zoolinnean/zlw028}}</ref>), also known as '''Grant's lesser bushbaby''' or the '''Mozambique lesser bushbaby''', is a species of [[primate]] in the family [[Galagidae]]. It is found in [[Malawi]], [[Mozambique]], [[Tanzania]], and [[Zimbabwe]]. Its natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical dry [[forest]]s. It is a common species and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] has assessed its conservation status as being of \"[[Least-concern species|least concern]]\".<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==Description==\nGrant's bushbaby is a small galago with a long, slender, well-furred tail. The sexes are similar. The forehead is pale grey and the crown darker grey, the eyes are surrounded by blackish eye-rings, and this black colour continues along the snout. There is a pale band running down the snout from forehead to nostrils. The ears are long and broad, with rounded tips, and are black on the outside. The general colour of the pelage is drab brown, the tip of each hair being buffy-brown. The outside of each limb is drab brown, gradually fading to whitish at the feet. The cheeks, throat and underparts are creamy-buff, the basal part of each hair being grey. The tail is elongated and bushy, drab brown with a blackened tip.<ref name=Kingdon>{{cite book|author1=Jonathan Kingdon|author2=David Happold|author3=Thomas Butynski|author4=Michael Hoffmann|author5=Meredith Happold|author6=Jan Kalina|title=Mammals of Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B_07noCPc4kC&pg=PA454 |year=2013 |publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-1-4081-8996-2 |pages=454\u2013455}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nGrant's bushbaby is native to Tanzania, Malawi, Mozambique and Zimbabwe. It occurs near the East African coast in the area between the [[Rufiji River]] in Tanzania, southwards to the [[Limpopo River]] in southern Mozambique. There are also inland populations, separate from the coastal ones. It occurs at least as high as {{convert|1800|m|ft|-2|abbr=on}} in the [[Thyolo Mountains]] in Malawi and in the [[Chimanimani]] region of Zimbabwe. It inhabits coastal and montane mixed forest, gallery forests and [[miombo]] woodland.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Galagidae nav}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q28156643}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:bushbaby, Grant's}}\n[[Category:Galagos|Grant's bushbaby]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Malawi]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Fauna of East Africa]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1907|Grant's bushbaby]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Tom Radulovich", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution and habitat:link to Chimanimani District", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grant%27s_bushbaby"}
{"title_page": "Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics", "text_new": "{{main|Rowing at the Summer Olympics}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox Olympic event\n| event       = Rowing\n| games       = 2004 Summer\n| image       = Rowing, Athens 2004.png\n| image_size  = 150px\n| caption     = \n| venue       = [[Schinias Olympic Rowing and Canoeing Centre]]\n| dates       = 14\u201322 August\n| competitors = 557\n| nations     = 55\n| prev        = [[Rowing at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000]]\n| next        = [[Rowing at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008]]\n}}\n{{Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics}}\n\n'''[[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]] at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]''' took place at the [[Schinias Olympic Rowing and Canoeing Centre]] and featured 550 competitors taking part in 14 events.<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/2004/ROW/ |title=Rowing at the 2004 Athens Summer Games |work=Sports Reference |accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe medals were split among 22 countries, [[Romania]] topping the medal table, their women winning 3 golds, with the traditionally strong [[Germany]], [[Great Britain]] and [[Australia]] picking up four medals in total.\n\nRomania's [[Elisabeta Lip\u0103]] won her fourth consecutive Olympic gold medal and fifth overall.  Lip\u0103, who was part of Romania's [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's eight|women's eight]], won her first in Los Angeles in 1984 followed by gold medals in 1992, 1996, 2000 and 2004, a record span of 20 years between her first and last gold medal.  It was also her eighth overall, which is more than any other rower, having won a silver and a bronze in 1988 and an additional silver in 1992. In winning her medal at age 39, Lip\u0103 became the oldest rower to win a gold medal and the oldest athlete in an endurance sport to win a gold medal.\n\n[[Image:USA Men's Lightweight Four Athens 2004.jpg|thumb|left|275px|Team USA competes in the lightweight four rowing competition.]]\n\n[[Matthew Pinsent]] also won his fourth consecutive medal, this time without legendary partner [[Steve Redgrave]].  The British men's [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's coxless four|coxless four]] of [[Steve Williams (rower)|Steve Williams]], [[James Cracknell]], [[Ed Coode]] with Pinsent at stroke narrowly saw off the challenge of the World Champion Canadian crew of [[Cameron Baerg]], [[Thomas Herschmiller]], [[Jake Wetzel]] and [[Barney Williams (rower)|Barney Williams]].  It was a dramatic stretch run with the lead literally changing hands with each stroke.  (In rowing, the boat will surge depending on where the rowers are during the stroke. Pinsent would later say that he thought they had won because they were in the best part of the stroke when they crossed the line).  Great Britain won with a time of 6:06.98, just 8/100ths of a second faster than the Canadians.  Pinsent later wept at the medal ceremony.\n\nMatching Lip\u0103's and Pinsent's feat of four consecutive gold medals was German sculler [[Kathrin Boron]] in the [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's quadruple sculls|women's quadruple sculls]].  She had won the doubles event in Barcelona 1992 and Sydney 2000 and the quadruple sculls in Atlanta 1996.\n\nAustralian [[James Tomkins (rower)|James Tomkins]], competing in his fifth games at the age of 39, won his third gold medal, and fourth medal overall, teaming with his longtime partner [[Drew Ginn]] in the [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's coxless pair|men's pair]]. Tomkins and Ginn had been part of the straight four that won the gold medal at the [[1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Atlanta Olympics]], and they had won the 1999 World Championship in the pair, but Ginn had missed the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Olympics]] with a severe back injury, and Tompkins had finished third with a new partner [[Matthew Long (rower)|Matthew Long]] in the pair.  Tomkins was also the oldest male rower to win an Olympic gold medal, surpassing Steve Redgrave.\n\nNorway's [[Olaf Tufte]] won the [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's single sculls|men's single scull]], and Germany's [[Katrin Rutschow-Stomporowski]] won with [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's single sculls|women's single scull]] beating two-time defending Olympic Champion [[Ekaterina Karsten]].\n\nThe Romanian [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's coxless pair|women's pair]] of [[Georgeta Damian]] and [[Viorica Susanu]] took gold before doubling up to help their [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's eight|eight]] take gold, giving Damian her fourth Olympic Gold medal &mdash; having won 2 golds in Sydney in the same disciplines.\n\nThe [[United States at the Olympics|United States]] won the prestigious [[Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's eight|men's eight]] for the twelfth time overall and the first time since [[Rowing at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964]].  In the second preliminary heat, both the U.S. and Canadian crews broke the previous [[List of world records in rowing|world best time]], with the U.S. winning in 5:19.85, which stood as a world best time until the second World Cup regatta of 2012.<ref>http://www.worldrowing.com/events/2012-worldcup-2/mens-eight/heat/</ref> The United States would go on to win the final.\n\n==Medal summary==\n\n===Men's events===\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Single sculls <br>{{DetailsLink|Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's single sculls}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Olaf Tufte]]|NOR|2004 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[J\u00fcri Jaanson]]|EST|2004 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Ivo Yanakiev]]|BUL|2004 Summer}}\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Double sculls <br>{{DetailsLink|Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double sculls}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[S\u00e9bastien Vieilledent]]<br/> and [[Adrien Hardy]]|FRA|2004 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Iztok \u010cop]]<br/> and [[Luka \u0160pik]]|SLO|2004 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Rossano Galtarossa]]<br/> and [[Alessio Sartori]]|ITA|2004 Summer}}\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Quadruple sculls <br>{{DetailsLink|Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's quadruple sculls}}\n|{{FlagIOCteam|RUS|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Nikolay Spinyov]]<br>[[Igor Kravtsov]]<br>[[Aleksey Svirin]]<br>[[Sergey Fedorovtsev]]\n|{{FlagIOCteam|CZE|2004 Summer}}<br>[[David Kop\u0159iva]]<br>[[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Karas]]<br>[[Jakub Han\u00e1k]]<br>[[David Jirka]]\n|{{FlagIOCteam|UKR|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Serhiy Hryn (rower)|Serhiy Hryn]]<br>[[Serhiy Biloushchenko]]<br>[[Oleh Lykov]]<br>[[Leonid Shaposhnikov]]\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Coxless pair <br>{{DetailsLink|Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's coxless pair}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Drew Ginn]]<br/> and [[James Tomkins (rower)|James Tomkins]]|AUS|2004 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Sini\u0161a Skelin]]<br/> and [[Nik\u0161a Skelin]]|CRO|2004 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Donovan Cech]]<br/> and [[Ramon di Clemente]]|RSA|2004 Summer}}\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Coxless four <br>{{DetailsLink|Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's coxless four}}\n|{{FlagIOCteam|GBR|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Steve Williams (rower)|Steve Williams]]<br>[[James Cracknell]]<br>[[Ed Coode]]<br>[[Matthew Pinsent]]\n|{{FlagIOCteam|CAN|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Cameron Baerg]]<br>[[Thomas Herschmiller]]<br>[[Jake Wetzel]]<br>[[Barney Williams (rower)|Barney Williams]]\n|{{FlagIOCteam|ITA|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Lorenzo Porzio]]<br>[[Dario Dentale]]<br>[[Luca Agamennoni]]<br>[[Raffaello Leonardo]]\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Coxed eight <br>{{DetailsLink|Rowing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's eight}}\n|{{FlagIOCteam|USA|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Jason Read]]<br>[[Wyatt Allen]]<br>[[Chris Ahrens (rower)|Chris Ahrens]]<br>[[Joseph Hansen (rower)|Joseph Hansen]]<br>[[Matt Deakin]]<br>[[Dan Beery]]<br>[[Beau Hoopman]]<br>[[Bryan Volpenhein]]<br>[[Peter Cipollone]] (cox)\n|{{FlagIOCteam|NED|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Matthijs Vellenga]]